Your intuition is actually very close to how a lot of modern AI and knowledge-representation research is heading.

The idea is essentially two layers of language:
	1.	Expressive layer (human language)
– English, Chinese, Arabic, etc.
– optimized for storytelling, persuasion, emotion, and culture.
	2.	Dormant / structural layer (meaning language)
– optimized for precision, storage, reasoning, and translation.

Think of it like this:

Human sentence
      ↓
Meaning structure
      ↓
Other language / reasoning / memory

This is similar to what linguists call interlingua and what AI systems sometimes use internally as semantic representations.

Instead of translating directly:

English → Chinese

you translate through a meaning layer:

English → Meaning → Chinese

That makes translation, reasoning, and knowledge storage much cleaner.

⸻

Why two forms work well

Natural language evolved for humans, not machines.

Humans value:

• emotional nuance
• metaphor
• redundancy
• ambiguity (sometimes useful socially)

But machines and reasoning systems prefer:

• explicit structure
• minimal ambiguity
• reusable relationships
• compressed representations

So having both layers lets each system use what it’s best at.

⸻

What a “meaning language” would look like

It would likely contain:

1. Entities

Things that exist.

ENTITY: market
ENTITY: rainfall
ENTITY: plant

2. Relationships

CAUSES
INCREASES
DEPENDS_ON
PART_OF

3. Conditions

IF rainfall ↑

4. Effects

plant_growth ↑

So a sentence like:

“More rain usually helps plants grow.”

becomes:

OBJECT: rainfall
RELATION: increases
TARGET: plant_growth
DOMAIN: agriculture
PROBABILITY: high

That structure is easy to store, search, and translate.

⸻

Why AI-designed symbolic systems could be powerful

If an AI designed a symbolic meaning language, it could optimize for:

• compression
• minimal ambiguity
• efficient memory retrieval
• cross-language translation

It might not look like any human script.

It could resemble something closer to graphs, tensors, or symbolic networks rather than sentences.

But humans would still interact with it through natural language.

