The 7 Rules for Structured Reasoning Language

These rules make language logical without making it unreadable.

⸻

Rule 1 — Define terms once

Every important concept gets a stable definition.

Example:

DELAYED_FEEDBACK =
a system where actions produce effects after a time delay

Later sentences can reuse the term.

This prevents meaning drift.

⸻

Rule 2 — Make relationships explicit

Every claim should include the relationship type.

Examples:

A causes B
A increases B
A limits B
A depends_on B

Avoid vague verbs like “affects”.

⸻

Rule 3 — Separate condition from claim

Statements should distinguish when they apply.

Example:

Instead of:

Exercise makes people healthier.

Use:

IF exercise_frequency ↑
THEN probability(health_improvement) ↑
DOMAIN: long-term lifestyle


⸻

Rule 4 — Identify the domain

Truth often depends on context.

Add domain markers.

DOMAIN: biology
DOMAIN: economics
DOMAIN: psychology

This prevents overgeneralization.

⸻

Rule 5 — Mark uncertainty

Not all claims are absolute.

Use confidence markers:

certainty: high
probability: medium
evidence: weak

This keeps reasoning honest.

⸻

Rule 6 — Prefer relationships over descriptions

Describe how things interact, not just what they are.

Example:

Weak:

“Markets are unstable.”

Better:

speculation ↑ → volatility ↑ → instability ↑


⸻

Rule 7 — Compress reusable patterns

If a pattern repeats, give it a name.

Example:

SUPPRESSION_LOOP =
pressure suppressed → accumulation → sudden release

Now you can apply it to:

• markets
• ecosystems
• psychology
• politics.

